ntained in a complex state. Yet few scholars have explored this process and the ways in which it changes, especially outside the Western world.Messick brings together intensive ethnography and textual analysis from a wealth of material: Islamic jurisprudence, Yemeni histories, local documents. In exploring the structure and transformation of literacy, law, and statecraft in Yemen, he raises important issues that are of comparative significance for understanding political life in other Muslim and nonwestern states as well.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDiplomatics, ArabicxHistoryxYemen (Republic). 0aDiplomatics, ArabiczYemen (Republic)xHistory. 0aIslamxYemen (Republic). 0aIslamzYemen (Republic). 0aIslamic lawxYemen (Republic). 0aIslamic lawzYemen (Republic). 0aManuscripts, ArabicxPublic opinionxYemen (Republic). 0aManuscripts, ArabiczYemen (Republic)xPublic opinion. 0aPublic opinionxYemen (Republic). 0aPublic opinionzYemen (Republic). 4aAnthropology. 4aCultural & Social. 4aSocial Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aMessick, Brinkley, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052020515440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091782840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520917828423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520917828/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles